Bird calling from a plant stalk in a harvested field.

Background sounds: wind (bursts up to 20km/h)

Distance: >10m

Equipment: Tascam DR-100mkIII + Sennheiser ME66/K6 + Rycote Super Softie

Edits: -12dB high-pass filter at 2700Hz
Calls from bird flying along edge of reservoir.

**Comments**: Passer-by's steps can be heard from 0:06 onwards.

**Recording modifications**: High-pass filter 12dB, 1000Hz. Normalized (DC offset, peak amplitude to -2.0 dB). Modified using Audacity.

**Habitat (inc. vegetation and level)**: Wheat field between a suburb and a major road, with a path going across. Bird located atop of a wheat stem.

**Behaviour**: Bird calling spontaneously in the evening from atop a wheat stem. Another bird joined it on a nearby wheat (same species, not vocalizing).

**Sex (with ID cues)**: None.

**Weather and other conditions**: Humid evening, with approaching clouds and rain.

**Comments on other birds**: Another *Motacilla flava* joined the bird on a wheat stem near to the one with the recorded bird. The other wagtail was not vocalizing.

recordings.rmk:
Interesting subdued song among reeds, unfortunately many other birds chirping around.


 2nd april 2019 edit: 
at the beginning I uploaded this file as Acrocephalus melanopogon subsong, after two years I have been able to hear the same song with the bird in full sight and it was a male Motacilla flava… so the first time I was misleaded by the presence of several bird species all together and I wrongly ascribed the song to Moustached warbler, I'm sorry.
